# Documentation Rules

Default: do **not** generate **member-level** XML doc comments (`/// <summary>`) unless Tier 1/2 applies, or the user explicitly asks. Prefer names and signatures that are self-explanatory — `IDamageModifier.Modify(float damage, DamageContext ctx)` needs no member comment. Every **public type** still needs the Tier 3 one-line summary (see below).

Explain **why**, not **what**, for member-level docs and inline comments. Do not restate the next line of code in a comment. (Type-level summaries under Tier 3 below are a narrow, explicitly-scoped exception — see there.)

## XML cross-references

In XML doc comments, name **same-type** members (fields, properties, methods on the documented type) with `<c>Name</c>` — not `<see cref="Name"/>`. Reserve `<see cref="…"/>` for **other types** (or their members) the reader may navigate to. Enum members on the documented enum (e.g. `<c>True</c>` on `DamageType`) follow the same rule.

## When XML docs are allowed (three tiers)

Judge by **role**, not by a fixed class-name whitelist. Examples below are illustrative.

### Tier 1 — Project-wide contracts

Cross-cutting APIs that define how layers talk to each other (typically Core, but not limited to the Core folder). Full XML is appropriate: `/// <summary>`, `<typeparam>`, `<exception>`, `<remarks>` as needed.

Examples: `IEvent`, `IEventBus`, `IState`, `StateMachine`, `IReadOnlyStatCollection`.

Concrete types that only implement a Tier-1 interface: use `/// <inheritdoc/>` on matching public members instead of duplicating docs.

### Tier 2 — Public APIs with non-obvious contracts

**Public** members whose **preconditions, thrown exceptions, value provenance, or intended call path** cannot be inferred from the signature alone. Cross-asmdef consumption is a typical case, not the gate — same-assembly public members (e.g. `Damageable.ClampCurrentHealthToMax`) qualify when the why is non-obvious. Self-explanatory public members (simple getters, obvious mutators) stay Tier 3.

Document with a short `/// <summary>`; add `<exception>` when throws encode usage protocol; add `<remarks>` on the type only for cross-cutting invariants (e.g. shared bus with `StatCollection`). Do **not** require full Tier-1 docs (`<typeparam>` tours, long remarks).

Non-obvious contract includes:
- **Usage protocol** — call order or initialization (e.g. `GetValue` before `SetBaseStat` → `InvalidOperationException`).
- **Domain validation on open types** — reject values the type system still allows (e.g. negative `float` damage/heal).
- **Value provenance** — who sets a field and when (e.g. `DamageContext.IsCrit` rolled at the ability layer via `IRandomProvider`, not inside the pipeline).
- **Visibility / call path** — public but not the normal entry point (e.g. clamp normally driven by `StatChangedEvent`).

**When is a thrown exception part of the public contract?** Document it when the parameter type allows illegal values **and** real or architecturally allowed call paths can pass variable/computed values into this API (e.g. pipeline output, ability math). Omit documentation for constructor null checks on required dependencies and other guards the signature already implies — fail-fast, not usage protocol.

Examples: `StatCollection.AddModifier` / `GetValue`; `Damageable.TakeDamage` / `Heal` (negative amount → `ArgumentOutOfRangeException`); `DamageContext.IsCrit` (provenance); `Damageable.ClampCurrentHealthToMax` (normal path vs public escape hatch).

Usually **omit** documenting every `ArgumentNullException` — prefer exceptions that encode **usage protocol** (call A before B, or else throw).

### Tier 3 — Everything else

Members: no XML. Self-explanatory public members and internal helpers stay uncommented.

Types: every **public** class/interface/struct/enum still gets at least one `/// <summary>` line, even when none of its members qualify for Tier 1/2 and would otherwise get zero documentation. This is a portfolio/reviewer-legibility floor, not a contract-documentation tier — it exists so opening `StatType.cs` or `StatModifierType.cs` cold gives an immediate sense of the type's role, without implying its members carry any usage protocol worth documenting. Tier 3 is a **floor**, not a ceiling: if the type later carries cross-cutting invariants, add `<remarks>` under Tier 2 rules.

This one line is the **only** place a slight lean toward "what" is acceptable — naming the type's role or boundary (e.g. "Additive or Percent contribution applied to a Stat's raw value" for `StatModifierType`) is fine, since a type has no "next line of code" to restate. It must not:
- restate the type name (`StatType` → ~~"Represents a stat type"~~)
- turn into a members list or usage tutorial
- migrate down onto members — a member with no Tier 1/2 justification still gets nothing, regardless of how well-documented its parent type is

`internal` types may skip this line entirely. If an internal type sits at a place a reader might reasonably expect public visibility (e.g. `StatValueValidation`), replace the summary with a one-line reason it's internal instead (e.g. `// Internal validation helpers; not part of the public Stats API surface.`).

## Line length

Wrap `///` XML doc lines and `//` inline comments at **120 characters**. Break at phrase boundaries; continue on the next doc or comment line with the same prefix (`///` or `//`). Prefer shorter lines when a remark is only one or two sentences — do not pad to 120.

## Voice — avoid AI-flavored docs

This section governs **wording**, not structure. Tier 1/2/3 still decide whether a
`summary` / `remarks` / `<exception>` belongs; Voice only cuts fluff once those tags are justified.

Prefer short, specific contracts over polished essays. Good docs sound like a teammate warning about a footgun, not a generated API brochure.

Signs to cut or rewrite:

- **Defensive framing** — "Not redundant with…", "It is important to note…", "By design…" as padding
- **Restating the summary in remarks** — if the type summary already says "Shared", don't open remarks with "Construct once and share…"
- **Stacking every why in one remark** — pick the non-obvious call-path reason; leave implementation trivia to `architecture.mdc`
- **Step-list summaries** that only narrate the method body — keep side effects that aren't obvious from the signature; drop the rest
- **Uniform templates** across sibling types ("Published on X by Y after Z") — vary wording; put the real contract in remarks
- **Marketing / jargon padding** — "diminishing-returns curve", "composition-root contract" when a plain sentence works

## Inline comments

Add a **one-line** inline comment only where the code deliberately differs from the obvious approach and a fast reader might assume a bug. Multi-fact architecture decisions belong in `architecture.mdc` / local `ARCHITECTURE_Detailed.md`, not pasted into source.

```csharp
// Correct — one line, explains the non-obvious part
// DoT bypasses DamagePipeline by design — TakeDamage only, no DamageEvent attribution.
public void OnTick(BuffInstance instance, ICombatEntity target, float deltaTime)
{
    target.Damageable.TakeDamage(instance.Config.DamagePerSecond * deltaTime);
}
```

Wrong: multi-sentence “architecture essays” above a method, or comments that only narrate what the code already says.
